summary.seg: This manuscript, copied between the 1550s and 1560s, is the first of a two-volume set of Greek literary texts with Cambridge, Christ's College, MS Rouse 359. MS Rouse 358 contains the Iliad, the Odyssey, the Batrachomyomachia and hymns by Homer.

According to the date appearing at the beginning of sections and a statement at the end of the manuscript, the manuscript was entirely copied by Carolus Stephanus in 1552. He claims to have copied the manuscript for personal study; he may not have completed it until some time after 1552. Little is known about him: he served as librarian of Johann Jakob Fugger (1516-1575), one of the most prolific book collectors of the 16th century, and is known to have catalogued in 1565 the Greek and Greek-Latin manuscripts of Fugger's collection, which later entered the Bayerische Staatsbibliothek in Munich, where Stephanus' autograph catalogue is kept: Munich, BSB, Cbm Cat. 48 (see also S. Kellner, A. Spethmann 1996, p. 514). Stephanus also copied a Greek psalter, Karlsruhe, Badische Landesbibliothek, Codex 431.

Although MS 358 seems never to have been divided into two volumes, the manuscript is conceived in two sections, called "tomi" by the copyist, who starts new pagination at the beginning of the second tome.

The manuscript was presented to Christ's College Library by William Henry Denham Rouse, Fellow of the College from 1888 to 1894, Honorary Fellow from 1933 until his death, and headmaster of the Perse School in Cambridge.

support.material:
pp. sect. 1, p. [i] - sect. 2, p. [619] Western paper, in folio. Watermarks:
Letter K ( 26 26 ) middle of the folio, between chainlines comparable to Briquet, Lettre K 8263 . The majority of those examples are dated to between 1550s and 1560s.
Greek cross in a circle on three mounts with four circles ( 35 35 ) middle of the folio, on a chainlines comparable to Piccard, 16-10-2896 . The majority of those examples are dated to 1560s.
Unidentified (geometric figures within a circle ( 40 40 ) middle of the folio, on a chainlines.
Sect. 1, p. [iii-iv] thick parchment, added for painting.

supportDesc.foliation: sect. 1: pp. [i-vi] + 1-679 + [680-688]; sect. 2: pp. [i-iv] + 1-617 + [618-622]. Original pagination in ink in Arabic numerals on external upper corner. It starts from the first page of the text of each tome.

collation.p:
The manuscript consists of 65 quires (sect, 1: quires 1-34; sect. 2: quires 35-65):
Quire 110+1 pp. [i]-16
Quires 2-3310 pp. 17-656
Quire 3416 pp. 657-[688]
Quires 35-4510 pp. [i]-216
Quire 4612 pp. 217-240
Quires 47-6410 pp. 241-600
Quire 6510+1 pp. 601-[620]
collation.catchwords: Original horizontal catchwords on every page with text, on right-hand corner.
collation.signatures: Original quire signatures in brown ink in Latin letters, on the first folio of each quire, recto, bottom left. Sequence restarts in sect. 2. Sect. 1: A (p. [v]) - I, K-T, V, X-Z, AA-II, KK-LL. Sect. 2: B (p. 17) - E (F coverd by glued decoration), G-I, K-T, V-Z, AA-GG.

handNote.p: The manuscript is entirely written by Carolus Stephanus Stephanus, Carolus in mixed minuscule, characterized by marked contrast between thick and thin strokes, the cursive style and the large size of capital letters.

decoDesc.decoNote: A portrait of Homer with a swan on sect. 1, p. [iii].
Numerous stencilled ornaments placed to fill in empty spaces at the end of books or to separate hypotheses from books, e.g.: sect. 1, pp. 64, 65, 86, 87.

Oval printed frames have been glued on the pages that serve as frontispieces of the two tomes (sect. 1, p. [i]; sect. 2, p. [iii]) and the first pages of the Batrachomyomachia (sect. 2, p. 520). Other rectilinear frames have been glued around the Latin translations of the hypotheses to the books of the Iliad (e.g. sect. 1, p. [vi]) and the Odyssey (e.g. sect. 2, p. [iv]).

additions.p: A circular book-plate pasted on sect. 1, pp. [v] and 8 containing the three coats of arms of the city of Nuremberg and that of the Behaim von Schwarzburg family of Nuremberg connected by loops; lettered above Bib: Nor: (Bibliotheca Norica) (cf. F. Warnecke, Die deutschen Bücherzeichen (ex-libris), Berlin 1890, no. 1473).

binding.p: Light brown parchment over paste-laminate boards. The thongs are laced through the parchment joints and pasted onto the inner side of the boards. There are four slits through each board that were for fastenings. Some slits and punched holes are present on the cover that might indicate reuse of the parchment. Lettering on the left board and the spine with titles of contents. Sprinkled red and blue on the edges.

history.origin: The manuscript was copied by Carolus Stephanus in 1552, in all likelihood in Augsburg (Germany). Some texts seem to have been added by Carolus Stephanus many years later, as suggested by the presence of the German text on sect. 1, p. [680], which corresponds to the 1599 revision of the 1564 translation.
history.provenance: Bookplates indicate the volume was owned by Behaim von Schwarzburg family of Nuremberg.
history.acquisition: Presented to Christ's College in 1940 by William Henry Denham Rouse (1863-1950) Rouse, W.H.D. (William Henry Denham), 1863-1950 , Fellow of the College from 1888 to 1894, Honorary Fellow from 1933 until his death, and headmaster of the Perse School in Cambridge.
